\[f(x)~=~ax^2+bx+c\]

  • \(c=\)

Combine the quadratic terms. The quadratic coefficients are {-2 , 8 , -3}, and their sum is 3.

\[{-2}x^{2}+{8}x^{2}-{3}x^{2}~\equiv~ 3x^2\]

Combine the linear terms. The linear coefficients are {5 , 9 , -8}, and their sum is 6.

\[{5}x+{9}x-{8}x~\equiv~ 6x\]

Combine the constant terms. The constant coefficients are {-4 , 6 , 7}, and their sum is 9.

\[{-4}+{6}+{7}~\equiv~ 9\]

Thus, we can write the function in standard form.

\[f(x)~=~{3}x^{2}+{6}x+{9}\]

\[a=3\] \[b=6\] \[c=9\]

where \(a\), \(b\), and \(c\) are integers.

  • What is the value of \(c\)?

You could use the box method.


Or, you can FOIL...


Either way, you should first get \[{-16}x^{2}+{16}x-{28}x+{28}\]

And, after combining like terms, you should get \[{-16}x^{2}-{12}x+{28}\]

Thus, \(a=-16\) and \(b=-12\) and \(c=28\). This question specifically asked for the value of \(c\), so the answer is \(28\).

The quadratic polynomial \(p(x)\) is defined below.

\[p(x)~=~x^{2}+{3}x-{54}\]

Which two linear polynomials are factors of \(p(x)\)?

You can get this by guessing and checking. Eventually you might guess the following:

\[p(x) ~=~ (x-{6})\cdot(x+{9})\]

You can check by using polynomial multiplication (in this case you can use the FOIL method).

* \(x\) \(-6\)
\(x\) \(x^2\) \({-6}x\)
\(9\) \({9}x\) \(-54\)

\[p(x) ~=~ x^{2}-{6}x+{9}x-{54}\]

\[p(x) ~=~ x^{2}+{3}x-{54}\]

After you've done this a few hundred times, you'll notice that you wanted two numbers that added to give 3 and multiplied to give -54. So, you start thinking of factor pairs of -54 until you find a pair that sums to 3. You will see that below I've listed all factor pairs of -54, along with the corresponding polynomials in factored and expanded forms.

Factor pairs of -54 Factored polynomial Expanded polynomial
1 and -54 \((x+{1})\cdot (x-{54})\) \(x^{2}-{53}x-{54}\)
-1 and 54 \((x-{1})\cdot (x+{54})\) \(x^{2}+{53}x-{54}\)
2 and -27 \((x+{2})\cdot (x-{27})\) \(x^{2}-{25}x-{54}\)
-2 and 27 \((x-{2})\cdot (x+{27})\) \(x^{2}+{25}x-{54}\)
3 and -18 \((x+{3})\cdot (x-{18})\) \(x^{2}-{15}x-{54}\)
-3 and 18 \((x-{3})\cdot (x+{18})\) \(x^{2}+{15}x-{54}\)
6 and -9 \((x+{6})\cdot (x-{9})\) \(x^{2}-{3}x-{54}\)
-6 and 9 \((x-{6})\cdot (x+{9})\) \(x^{2}+{3}x-{54}\)

And, so, \(x^{2}+{3}x-{54}\) is an equivalent expression to \((x-{6})\cdot(x+{9})\), which is also equivalent to \((x+{9})\cdot(x-{6})\).

Consider the expression:

\[{15}x^{2}+{9}x+{10}x+{6}\]

Notice that the product of the quadratic coefficient and the constant is 90.

\[(15)(6)=90\]

Also the product of both linear coefficients is 90. \[(9)(10)=90\]

Since both of those products match, we are set up for factoring by grouping.

When the expression is factored into factored form, what are the two factors?

\[{15}x^{2}+{9}x+{10}x+{6}\]

The first two terms are \(15x^2\) and \(9x\). The greatest common factor of those two terms is \({3}x\). Factor out \({3}x\) from the first two terms.

\[{3}x({5}x+{3})+{10}x+{6}\]

The last two terms are \(10x\) and \(6\). The greatest common factor of those two terms is \(2\). Notice, I am picking the sign (positive or negative) so that both expressions in parentheses will match. Factor out \(2\) from the last two terms.

\[{3}x({5}x+{3})+2({5}x+{3})\]

We now have two terms: \({3}x({5}x+{3})\) and \(2({5}x+{3})\). Notice, both terms share a factor of \({5}x+{3}\), so we can now get the expression in fully factored form. (By using distributive property... backwards...)

\[({3}x+{2})({5}x+{3})\]

The first two terms are \(14x^2\) and \(4x\). The greatest common factor of those two terms is \({2}x\). Factor out \({2}x\) from the first two terms.

\[{2}x({7}x+{2})-{21}x-{6}\]

The last two terms are \(-21x\) and \(-6\). The greatest common factor of those two terms is \(-3\). Notice, I am picking the sign (positive or negative) so that both expressions in parentheses will match. Factor out \(-3\) from the last two terms.

\[{2}x({7}x+{2})-3({7}x+{2})\]

We now have two terms: \({2}x({7}x+{2})\) and \(-3({7}x+{2})\). Notice, both terms share a factor of \({7}x+{2}\), so we can now get the expression in fully factored form. (By using distributive property... backwards...)

\[({2}x-{3})({7}x+{2})\]

If that was confusing, I recommend checking out the article.

Please review this article on factoring by grouping.

Consider the expression:

\[{6}x^{2}-{16}x+{9}x-{24}\]

Notice that the product of the quadratic coefficient and the constant is -144.

\[(6)(-24)=-144\]

Also the product of both linear coefficients is -144. \[(-16)(9)=-144\]

Since both of those products match, we are set up for factoring by grouping.

When the expression is factored into factored form, what are the two factors?

\[{6}x^{2}-{16}x+{9}x-{24}\]

The first two terms are \(6x^2\) and \(-16x\). The greatest common factor of those two terms is \({2}x\). Factor out \({2}x\) from the first two terms.

\[{2}x({3}x-{8})+{9}x-{24}\]

The last two terms are \(9x\) and \(-24\). The greatest common factor of those two terms is \(3\). Notice, I am picking the sign (positive or negative) so that both expressions in parentheses will match. Factor out \(3\) from the last two terms.

\[{2}x({3}x-{8})+3({3}x-{8})\]

We now have two terms: \({2}x({3}x-{8})\) and \(3({3}x-{8})\). Notice, both terms share a factor of \({3}x-{8}\), so we can now get the expression in fully factored form. (By using distributive property... backwards...)

\[({2}x+{3})({3}x-{8})\]

If that was confusing, I recommend checking out the article.
